<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>TRANSPORT SELECT COMMITTEE:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Dr John Disney (TIC 083)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Identifying </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">demand</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Demand is currently very poorly defined despite the wealth of data now available through electronic ticket machines on buses and rail ticket sales (although some rural bus services still use manual / handwritten </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">/ no tickets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Staffordshire and ma</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ny do not adequately record journeys made by Concessionary Pass Holders of passengers with multi-journey tickets).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Many LA’s make arbitrary decisions regarding tendered bus services based upon crude weekly / monthly / annual average numbers of passengers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">per journey and subsidy per passenger journey.  This takes no account of the patronage of specific journeys; effectively the inclusion of positioning journeys can distort the statistics and suggest that services are not being underused. Furthermore loading</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s on rural bus services are seasonal; not only do many rural bus services attract tourists in the summer (and often in the weekends during the winter) but local residents make more journeys at these times as there are more employment opportunities and elde</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rly people do not like travelling anywhere in poor weather.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These crude averages are also used to determine the required vehicle size, irrespective of variation in loadings between journeys, resulting in suppressed demand as passengers fear being left beh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ind by a full bus (especially as many smaller buses cannot carry standees).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Calculations of the subsidy per passenger journey often do not take account of reimbursement from concessionary fares or multi-journey tickets</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; when included these are often very </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">low.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Rural rail services tend to remain basically unaltered even when the TOC changes as they are basically specified in the franchise agreement although some TOC’s operate additional services for operational efficiency or to cater for additional </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(seasonal) demand, especially if the franchise terms allow them to benefit from the additional revenue generated. It is very rare for trains to be so full that passengers cannot board although sometimes overcrowding on lines like the Settle – Carlisle  can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> exceed peak London commuter journeys.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">User needs</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Many LA’s make changes to rural bus services without any notification to or consultation with passengers affected; indeed revised timetables are often not available until 2 weeks or less before the change</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and roadside publicity is often not changed or new timetables are displayed alongside expired ones with no dates shown; I have seen 3 different versions of timetables displayed for some services. This is despite the requirement for changes to be notified </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to Traffic Commissioners with 56 days notice. Even websites are often vague about changes despite the LA concerned being the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">funder</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the service. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Few rural bus services are commercially provided but those that are tend to be better at publicity includi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ng forthcoming changes but these changes are usually implemented for commercial reasons with no user consultation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As LA budgets are squeezed, many long tern (3 and 5 year) contracts with operators are being terminated at short notice leading to operators</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> being reluctant to invest in vehicles or marketing for such services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Overall the needs of persons with limited mobility have been much better addressed in recent years due to DDA Regulations but this has increased operating cost by up to 25% as low floo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r buses are costly to maintain when used on poorer surfaced rural roads with adverse cambers and steep inclines.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Many services are designed around the shopping, health and welfare needs of older persons but give them little opportunity to socialise or par</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">take in activities and events in adjacent towns and villages as most services terminate around 1700 and do not operate on Sundays.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Young </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">persons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> needs are rarely met with few evening or Sunday services despite these being precisely the times when young pe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ople are more likely to find work especially in the tourism and hospitality sectors. A lack of early morning buses can also prevent them from accepting jobs although my research has uncovered young people reliant upon family members rising early to offer l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ifts or them walking or cycling up to 5 miles on unlit roads in the early morning.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Some LA’s do undertake consultation when major cuts are planned but the process is complex and not user friendly and the response rate is usually low. LA’s then falsely ass</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ume that the cuts will have little impact and implement them. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Challenges</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The major challenge is to provide an attractive service and being prepared to sustain it long enough to justify a sustained marketing campaign with just minor tweaks to the timetab</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">le. Many services previously supported by Rural Bus Grant / Challenge and LSTF have been short term and poorly marketed, often being substantially changed or withdrawn after as little as six months. Experience shows that it takes at least two years for a r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ural bus service to become established; the most successful services are those which have an established timetable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Rural bus services should be integrated with both existing commercial bus services </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and rail services, preferably with integrated ticketing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Connections should be guaranteed with buses waiting for trains and other buses; it is not feasible for trains to wait for buses. They should provide opportunities for both local residents to access the wider community and visitors to access the countrysi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">de. An excellent example is the  daily Little White Bus Hawes to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Garsdale</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Station service, whilst most buses in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ledbury</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are now routed past the railway station. However in Matlock the new bus station adjacent to the railway station (though it is impossible</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to see if the train has arrived from the bus station) is not used by most bus services (even those operated under LA contract or by the same transport group as the TOC).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Community Transport</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ct works well for some passengers especially the very elderly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or disabled who appreciate “door to door” services often with an escort. However they are very limited and normally require advance booking (up to 48 hrs ahead) and pre-registration with the scheme. The latter is often limited to elderly and disabled resid</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ents in the area, excluding younger people and visitors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Many CT vehicles are grossly underused being on the road only 35 hours per week and they could be used to provide early morning, evening and weekend bus services as timetabled routes, Revenue earned</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from this work would help to meet overheads and thus reduce the usually high cost </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of core services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">CT using paid drivers and management is not a cheap option and some LA’s are cutting back on such services </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Shropshire, whilst Harrogate &amp; District CT </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has recently gone into administration. On the other hand Lincolnshire Connect appears to be a viable model to benchmark against.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Both the Upper </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wensleydale</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Community Partnership (Little White Bus) and Western Dales Bus in the Yorkshire Dales have shown th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at both scheduled journeys and demand responsive journeys can be provided using volunteer drivers managed by a Board of enthusiastic and competent volunteers. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Taxis and DRT</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Many CT services are demand responsive although this term covers many different </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">modes from bespoke “dial a ride” services to extensions and diversions into villages requested by passengers already onboard; the latter is often used on return market day services and the last outward journey on other rural services to avoid the need to s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">erve every hamlet if there is no-one to set down.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Demand responsive services need to be open to everyone and to be able to accept “last minute bookings”. This requires consistent mobile telephone coverage and hands-free phone in the bus itself for the dri</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ver to be contacted either directly by passengers or through a control centre. This works very efficiently in Upper </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ensleydale</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> but is not an option in the Western Dales due to a lack of mobile signal in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dentdale</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Subsidised taxi scheme are rarely provide</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d in the UK yet they could be a cost effective alternative in some cases </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> providing connections between rail stations and their rural hinterland. The user should be expected to pay at least 50% of the cost.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Funding Challenges</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As LA’s grapple with dimin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ishing budgets it is all too easy for them to cut rural bus services and blame central government. Bus service cuts require no redundancies in the public sector (though they will lead to redundancies and reduced hours for bus drivers, mechanics and managem</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ent in the private sector) and there are no residual costs to consider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> redundant buildings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The following recommendations are made based upon my research:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Establishment of Community Interest Companies to manage the operation of small networks of rural</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> services; the Dales &amp; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bowland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Community Interest Company in the Yorkshire Dales is an excellent benchmark to follow. This was established in 2007 to restore the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ilkley</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Skipton</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Sunday bus service and now operates 13 Summer Sunday and 5 Winter Sunday ser</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vices across the Dales. It is owned by a registered charity and is managed entirely by volunteers but bus services are contracted out to commercial operators using paid drivers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Reforming BSOG to concentrate support upon rural bus services and all bus serv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ices operated early morning (between 0500 and 0700) and evenings (between 1900 and 2330) Mon – Sat and all day Sunday. This would require the classification of all bus routes in the UK based upon the population size served with support being inversely prop</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ortional to population size; BSOG should be withdrawn from weekday daytime urban and inter-urban bus services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and this funding used to increase BSOG for services to isolated communities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Encouraging seasonal timetables to be introduced on all rural routes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not just Summer Tourist services. We should accept the fact that many rural routes attract 75% of their annual patronage between Easter and September and plan accordingly.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ensure that rural bus services receive a fair return from Concessionary Fares. Based</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> upon the classification of routes proposed above, I would expect a sliding scale of reimbursement to be introduced with rural routes receiving 80% of the adult fare reducing to 50% on urban routes. This would allow sensible fares to be charged on rural bu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s services; at present there is a wide variation with some LA’s and operators justifying high single fares (£7 for 11 miles is the highest I have encountered) to get a reasonable return on concessionary journeys where the reimbursement rate is around 50%.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Introducing a £1 per journey charge for Concessionary Pass Holders on all services operating less than 52 days per year. This would be in addition to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">concessionary fares reimbursement thus encouraging operators to introduce seasonal timetables and also req</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">uiring users to contribute to the cost of operating such services.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>